R Project Extra Questions

These are the extra problems in the R project about Adult Dataset

setting the dataset up

Questions from document

1. How many men and women (sex feature) are represented in this dataset?

we can answer this using a bar chart, we can also use count. Thus, we have 21789 Males and 10771.

table 1

table 2

Observation: this gives us a ratio of almost 2 males to 1 females.
If we ask why we have more males to females, it may be because males are more willing to take the survey and give out personal information. On the other hand, females are more wary and less likely to give out personal information.

2. What is the average age (age feature) of women and men?

In order to find the average age of women and men, we have to use summarise function in the dplyr library

`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

Thus, the average age of women is 36.85 and the average age of men is 39.43.
Observation: the average ages between the sexes are pretty close.

3. What is the percentage of German/Chinese/Japanese/U.S. citizens (native-country feature)?

To find the percentage of the native-country feature, we should use plotting method called geom_bar, or we could use count to find the percentage. Thus, German is 0.42%, Chinese is 0.23%, Japanese is 0.19%, U.S. is 9.59%. Observation: USA has by far the greatest number of native-born in our data, maybe the data collectors focused on surveying Americans because of its population diversity.

table 1

table 2

4. What are the mean and standard deviation of age for those who earn more than 50K per year (salary feature) and those who earn less than 50K per year?

In order to get the mean and standard deviation for this we must use summarise and group_by. Thus, for those who have salary <= 50K, the mean of age is 36.78365, and standard deviation of age is 14.02037. For those who have salary > 50K, the mean of age is 44.24984, and standard deviation of age is 10.51903

`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

Observation: the lower earners tend to be younger people and the higher earner tend to be older people.

5. Is it true that people who earn more than 50K have at least high school education? (education – Bachelors, Prof-school, Assoc-acdm, Assoc-voc, Masters or Doctorate feature)

The direct answer is no, there are people who earn more than 50K and have lower education than high school. However, by looking at the second graph, there are more people with high education and 50K than having low education and 50K Thus, people would be more likely to earn more than 50K if they are a HS-grad and above.

1. My question: What is the average years of education for each occupation and each race?

race v education-num

occupation v education-num

Boxplot of asian and whites look the same, both with about the same medians and out-liers, black and amer-indian-eskimo also have very similar boxplots, both with lower medians and many out-liers. The race other has the lowest median, these may be mixed races or extreme minorities.

For education and occupation, we can see that the people in prof-specialty and exec-managerial by far have the most years in education. people in services have the least years of education.

7 My question: What is the relationship between marriage status and education num. Is it true that people with more education will less likely be in a relationship, because they are picky and driven in the work force.

`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

False, people who are married and is together with their spouse tends to have a more years in education, or people who have more years in education tend to be married and is together with their spouse. I believe it is that people with more education tends to be married and is together with their spouse. This may be because of finacial reasons because people who have more education tends to get a higer salary.

8 My question: Which kind of people tend to be widows, is it possible that there are aspects of the person that have a higher correlation with being a widow?

lets look at the data of widows, what kind of people were they?

average age of widow, and a boxplot

the age age of a widow is 58 years old, that is pretty old compared to our overall data which is 38 years old, also seeing that there are out-liers in the boxplot of people who are younger, we can tell that the overall age of widows are old and around 60.

sex and education of widows

most of the widows in the data set are females, which is unsurprising because females often outlive their spouse. They also had low education, majority of them where only highschool gradates, which is not surprising because they are very old and education wasn’t as easily accessible when these women where young.

9 My question: How does marriage affect Indian natives and what is the difference between males and females? Is it the same effect as marriage on the entire data set like in Question #1.

In Question #1 we observe that males who are married have the highest proportion of >50K earners and also work the most hours compared to other marital status. Females on the other hand, also have the highest proportion of >50K earners but no drastic change in working hours. ### males {.tabset} In our graphs divorced Indian males work the most hours, a whooping 55 hours.
